In .NET 10, `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` was removed because Android deprecated the underlying `adjustResize` mode. The replacement is the **edge-to-edge** layout model with `AndroidX.Core` window-insets handling.

**Quick fix — use the new `KeyboardResize` API:**

```csharp
// In MauiProgram.cs or your page
#if ANDROID
builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
{
    events.AddAndroid(android => android.OnCreate((activity, _) =>
    {
        // Ensures content resizes when keyboard appears
        AndroidX.Core.View.ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(
            activity.Window.DecorView, new InsetsListener());
    }));
});
#endif
```

Or more simply, in your `MainActivity.cs`:

```csharp
protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

    WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);
}
```

Then in your page/layout, set:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns:android="clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.AndroidSpecific;
             assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls"
             android:Application.WindowSoftInputModeAdjust="Resize">
```

**If that still doesn't work (common in .NET 10)**, the most reliable approach is:

```csharp
// Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs
[Activity(..., WindowSoftInputMode = SoftInput.AdjustPan)]
public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity { }
```

Combined with wrapping your chat input in a layout that responds to keyboard insets:

```xml
<Grid RowDefinitions="*,Auto">
    <CollectionView Grid.Row="0" ... />
    <Entry Grid.Row="1" Placeholder="Type a message..." />
</Grid>
```

**TL;DR:** Replace `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` with either:
1. `SoftInput.AdjustPan` in the Activity attribute (simplest), or
2. Adopt edge-to-edge + insets handling via `WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false)` for full control.

`AdjustPan` scrolls the view so the focused input is visible — usually sufficient for a chat screen.
